{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":29894,"record_hash":"sha256:d52cdc8af33e98fcc002cea52c9aa83c090eab99c05bdbb6d58f7e089cb4a2ca","timestamp":"2026-05-11T16:15:23.182Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"I think it reconciles pretty well, with one important caveat around transcript list dedupe.\n\nGitMeta’s model is:\n\n- SQLite is the local read/write/current-value store.\n- Serialization writes shareable metadata from SQLite into Git trees/commits.\n- Push sends those metadata refs over normal Git transport.\n- Pull/fetch gets remote metadata refs.\n- Materialize merges the remote metadata tree back into local SQLite.\n\nSo our current POC is only doing the first part: writing current local state into `.git/git-meta.sqlite`. It does not serialize, push, fetch, or materialize yet.\n\n**What Fits Well**\nOur choice to use `gitbutler:*` keys, not `meta:local:*`, is correct for future sharing. The spec says `meta:local:` keys are never serialized, so our current keys are eligible to become shareable once GitMeta serialization/push is enabled.\n\nThe current target shape also fits:\n\n```text\nproject\n  gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n  gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:...\n```\n\nThat means durable session data is project-scoped and can travel independently from branches. Later branch/PR/change associations can be sets on branch/change targets:\n\n```text\nbranch/change/commit target\n  gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n```\n\nSets are a good match for associations because materialization can merge them naturally and duplicate members collapse.\n\n**What Needs Care**\nThe transcript itself is currently a GitMeta list:\n\n```text\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:transcript = list<TranscriptRecord JSON>\n```\n\nThat fits GitMeta’s list model for append logs, and serialization would store each entry as its own blob, not one giant JSON array. Good.\n\nBut GitMeta lists intentionally allow duplicates. Our local dedupe works because we also store:\n\n```text\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:record-hashes = set<sha256:record>\n```\n\nThat prevents local re-capture duplication. After materialization from remote, that set also helps future local captures avoid appending records already captured elsewhere.\n\nThe caveat is concurrent capture before sync:\n\n1. laptop captures session record A\n2. desktop captures same session record A before pulling laptop metadata\n3. both serialize/push/merge\n4. GitMeta list materialization can contain two transcript entries for record A, because lists allow duplicates\n\nThe `record-hashes` set will dedupe the hash, but GitMeta itself will not remove duplicate JSON list entries by looking inside `record_hash`. That is application semantics.\n\nSo before we rely on push/materialize for real sharing, we should choose one of these:\n\n- Reader dedupes transcript entries by `record_hash` when displaying/exporting.\n- Materialization/import repair dedupes list entries by `record_hash`.\n- Change the storage shape from append-list to per-record keys, for example `...:record:<record-hash> = JSON`, plus an index/order set/list.\n\nFor the POC, current shape is fine. For cross-machine session handoff, I’d at least make readers dedupe by `record_hash`.\n\n**Push/Privacy**\nOnce serialized, these records are Git blobs pushed to a remote. We redacted values before storage, which is necessary, but this is still sensitive-by-default material. So “shareable-ready” should not mean “automatically pushed without policy.”\n\nGitMeta has serialize filters and `meta:local:*`; we are not using local-only keys because the future use cases are sharing-oriented. But before enabling automatic `git meta push`, we probably want explicit user/product policy:\n\n- opt-in to sharing agentlog metadata\n- maybe route `gitbutler:agent-session:**` to a separate/private metadata ref\n- maybe exclude `source_record` or tool fields under stricter modes\n\n**Bottom Line**\nThe design is aligned with GitMeta’s materialize/push model: SQLite now, shareable Git metadata later. Project-scoped durable sessions plus target-level association sets are a good fit.\n\nThe main thing I’d keep on our radar is transcript dedupe after remote materialization. GitMeta will merge the list; GitButler/agentlog needs to interpret it as “ordered transcript records keyed by `record_hash`,” not blindly trust list uniqueness.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T16:15:23.182Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}